description: {"blocks":[{"key":"5lkfd","text":"Quantifying crucial steps in gene regulation during transcription elongation, such as promoter-proximal pausing, requires high resolution methods to map the transcription machinery across the genome. Native Elongating Transcript sequencing (NET-seq) interrogates the 3' ends of nascent RNA through sequencing, providing a direct visualization of RNA Polymerase II (Pol II) positions genome-wide with strand specificity and single nucleotide resolution. As NET-seq does not require previous labeling of mRNA, it is ideally-suited for measuring nascent transcription in tissues. In brief, actively transcribing Pol II together with the nascent RNA is quantitatively purified from cells by cellular fractionation. To prevent run-on transcription, fractionation is performed in the presence of the potent Pol II inhibitor α-amanitin, which prevents NTP recognition and catalysis by the Pol II trigger loop. Then, the isolated nascent RNA is fragmented, converted into cDNA and processed into a sequencing library employing a minimal number of PCR cycles. The library preparation method is designed in a way that upon random fragmentation of the nascent transcripts, only the 3’ ends of nascent transcripts carrying a free hydroxy-group are sequenced. This reveals the position of transcriptionally engaged Pol II at nucleotide resolution.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"avvf5","text":"We modified the original NET-seq protocol (Mayer \u0026 Churchman, 2016) for application in murine liver tissue and named this new adaptation of the protocol tissue NET-seq (tNET-seq). The main change in the protocol pertains to the nuclei isolation. Fresh liver tissue were placed in ice-cold PBS, cut into small pieces and homogenized in nuclei isolation buffer (Sigma, NUC101) using a Dounce tissue homogenizer. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2s562","text":"A published analysis pipeline for NET-seq can be found at the Churchman lab Github.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":76,"length":6}],"data":{}},{"key":"7d9d8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"D86EB4D7132811EDB1220A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://github.com/churchmanlab/MiMB2019NETseq"}}}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cfs17","text":"Place the fresh liver tissue in ice-cold PBS, cut into smaller pieces and homogenize in 3 ml of nuclei isolation buffer using a Dounce tissue homogenizer (Wheaton). After complete homogenization, transfer the sample to a Falcon tube. Add 3 ml of nuclei isolation buffer to the remaining pieces in the tissue homogenizer, homogenize further and transfer the remnants also to the tube. Following an incubation on ice for 5 min, pass the samples through a 70-μm cell strainer and collect the nuclei by centrifuging at 500 x g for 20 min.","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1s0pu","text":"Resuspend the nuclei pellet in 4 ml of nuclei isolation buffer. After incubation on ice for 5 min, collect the nuclei by centrifuging at 500 x g for 5 min. To remove cytoplasmic remnants, wash the nuclei pellet with 1600 μl nuclei wash buffer and centrifuge at 1,150 x g for 5 min. Repeat the washing with 800 μl nuclei wash buffer. Then, gently resuspend the pellet in 200 µl of glycerol buffer using a cut 1,000-µl tip and transfer the suspension to a new 1.5-ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube. To lyse nuclei, add 400 µl of nuclei lysis buffer, mix samples by pulsed vortexing and incubate on ice for 20 min. After assessing nuclei lysis of a small aliquot under a light microscope, centrifuge the samples at 18,500 x g for 2 min. Completely remove the supernatant (nucleoplasmic fraction) and resuspend the chromatin pellet in 50 µl chromatin resuspension solution.","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

The resulting reads can be identified as they lack the random UMI sequence encoded on the linker and therefore align well to the reference genome both with and without UMI displacement: when the STAR alignment score of a read with the UMI sequence equals the UMI length (10nt) plus the alignment score from that read without UMI.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"eq1gs","text":"Use HTseq to generate a coverage (bedgraph) file containing the read counts at a base-pair resolution over the reference genome as determined from the 5’ end of the read alignments (without UMI) on the opposite strand. The resulting positions correspond to the 3’ ends of nascent RNA and thereby map RNA polymerase positions. The coverage files will be used for a variety of downstream bioinformatics analyses such as visual inspection (e.g. using IGV), metagene profiling (e.g. Bedtools), differential expression (e.g. DEseq2).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"360ip","text":"The western blot control is used to  determine whether or not the cellular fractionation protocol has been executed  successfully. The efficiency of the fractionation can be quantified by  measuring the amount of elongating Pol II captured in the chromatin fraction  (ideally≥95%). When the fractionation  protocol is being performed for the first time or being tested on a new cell  type, the cytoplasm, nucleoplasm, and chromatin fractions should be checked  for subcellular marker proteins (see Note 5) to confirm the fractionation is  working (see Note 20).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"e2usf","text":"Adjust the nucleoplasmic (from 3.3.2) and chromatin fraction (from 3.3.2) volumes to the cytoplasmic fraction (from 3.3.1) volume by adding 1× PBS. Mix each fraction well and ensure the chromatin pellet is completely resuspended (see Note 7).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cdqtp","text":"Add 50 µl of 2× SDS buffer (see section 2.3.2 step 7) to 50 µl of each subcellular fraction and boil the samples at 95 °C for 5 min (at this point, samples can be stored for months at −20 °C).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4eba","text":"Separate samples by standard SDS-PAGE (loading 10 µl of each boiled sample per lane is usually sufficient).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"58mbr","text":"Probe the membrane overnight at 4 °C with Pol II CTD Ser2-P antibody (3E10, 1:1,000 dilution) and Pol II CTD Ser5-P antibody (3E8, 1:1,000 dilution). These antibodies target transcribing RNA Pol II (see Note 6).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"b9e08","text":"Performing RNA fragmentation results in a homogeneous RNA pool which helps to avoid length biases in any downstream enzymatic reactions. The fragmentation test can be performed using total RNA (or any easily-obtained RNA sample). Once the appropriate fragmentation time is determined (where most of the RNA molecules range from 40 –110 nt), fragmentation can be performed on the nascent RNA (obtained from cellular fractionation) using the determined time (Figure 2); the size range of the nascent RNA and total RNA pools do not vary enough for the fragmentation time to be different. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d7h6k","text":"Take 9 samples of RNA from a total RNA sample (or any other easily obtained RNA sample), each sample should be 20 µl in volume and contain ~1ug of RNA. Add 20 µl of 2× alkaline fragmentation solution to each sample and mix well (see Note 32); fragmentation is not performed for the oGAB11 control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"umnn","text":"Fragment each RNA sample at 95 °C in a thermal cycler for the following times: 0, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, and 50 minutes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9nq82","text":"To purify the fragmented RNA, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"anp8v","text":"Prepare RNA ladder (denoted as L in figure) by adding 1.0 µl of RNA control ladder to 9 µl of RNase-free H2O. Add 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample to the RNA ladder and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7n00g","text":"Prepare all RNA samples by adding 1.0 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer to each sample, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"63mja","text":"Denature the RNA sample and RNA ladder for 2 min at 80 °C. Place the samples on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cssug","text":"Pre-run a 15% (wt/vol) polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel at 200 V for 15 min in 1× TBE. Thoroughly flush out gel wells prior to pre-running the gel (see Note 35).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cl0f5","text":"Load gel with the RNA ladder and the fragmented RNA sample. Separate by PAGE at 200 V for 65 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"f8ofo","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cgc2d","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light. The optimal fragmentation time is when most RNA molecules are in the required size range, between 40 and 110 nt (the optimal fragmentation time in the figure below is between 25 and 30 minutes).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dk201","text":"This protocol for rapidly extracting RNA or cDNA from a polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel is similar to the gel extraction protocol described by the Weissman laboratory (Ingolia et al. 2012; Churchman and Weissman 2012).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":163,"length":50}],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"5A3F7674C3FB11EBA0740A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://paperpile.com/c/KrctMJ/VdlnQ+PUyja"}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"30h0t","text":"Use a 21G needle to pierce the bottom of a 0.5-ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"af662","text":"Place the pierced 0.5-ml tube into a 1.5-ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ercfu","text":"Put the gel slice (from fragmentation, RT, or PCR) into the pierced 0.5-ml tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1b8f4","text":"Centrifuge the nestled tubes, containing the gel slice, at 20,000g for 4 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"7dq70","text":"Add 200 µl of RNase-free H2O to the chopped-up gel and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"1jtff","text":"Incubate the sample mixture for 10 min at 70 °C in a Thermomixer.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"dei8e","text":"Vortex the mixture for 30 s at medium intensity.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"37p61","text":"Cut the tip off of a 1,000-µl pipette tip and transfer the gel mixture into a microcentrifuge tube filter.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"bp18s","text":"Centrifuge the mixture at 20,000g for 3 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5q029","text":"The NET-seq library is PCR amplified using an Illumina index forward primer (Barcode primer, see Table 1) and a reverse primer (oNTI231; Table 1) specific to NET-seq (Figure 4). For each NET-seq library preparation, the minimum number of PCR cycles needed to obtain a sequencing library must to be determined. The NET-seq library is then amplified with the determined minimal amount of PCR cycles; this avoids overamplification which can result in unwanted products such as PCR duplicates.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3e1pi","text":"Prepare the PCR master mix (see section 2.4.8 step 4) for four pilot PCR amplifications for each cDNA sample and the oGAB11 cDNA control sample (denoted as O in figure). Mix well and store it on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ci3ko","text":"For each PCR sample, put 19 µl of PCR master mix in a 0.2-ml RNase-free PCR tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"7sf9l","text":"Add 1 µl of circularized cDNA and mix it well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5ptso","text":"Perform PCR pilot amplifications (described in Table 2). Remove one PCR tube for each sample at the end of the extension step after 6, 8, 10 and 12 amplification cycles.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"12fcr","text":"Add 3.4 µl of 6× DNA loading dye to each tube and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dh82u","text":"Prepare DNA control ladder (denoted as L in figure) by adding 1.0 µl of ladder to 9 µl of DNase-free H2O. Then add 2 µl of 6× DNA loading dye and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9ndpv","text":"Separate the PCR products and the DNA control ladder by TBE gel electrophoresis on an 8% (wt/vol) TBE gel at 180 V for 55 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1frc4","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution (see section 2.4.8) for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bqkqa","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light and identify the optimal PCR amplification cycles for each cDNA sequencing library. The optimal PCR amplification cycles for the NET-seq library, which runs at ~150 nt, is determined by the presence of a clear band at ~150 nt and no higher-molecular-weight PCR products (the optimal number of cycles in the figure below is between 6 and 8).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7j719","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.1 Preparation of buffers and working area for cellular fractionation. Prepare all buffers on the day of fractionation before collecting cells.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7qooc","text":"Spray down all worksurfaces, pipettes, etc. with RNase away.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.1 Preparation of buffers and working area for cellular fractionation. Prepare all buffers on the day of fractionation before collecting cells.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"29rmj","text":"Prepare CLB, SB, NWB, GB, NLB, and CRS buffers (see Materials section 1.1 for buffer components) and store all solutions on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.1 Preparation of buffers and working area for cellular fractionation. Prepare all buffers on the day of fractionation before collecting cells.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"c2tv4","text":"Make sure tabletop centrifuge is at 4 °C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fqd9i","text":"Cellular fractionation has been successfully performed on several different cell types (see Note 19 in the Guidelines section). The protocol was originally optimized for HeLa S3 or HEK293T cells (Mayer and Churchman 2016). When fractionating other cell types optimization may be required (see Note 20). Cells are ideally grown according to internationally recognized guidelines (such as those suggested by ENCODE) and handled according to the supplier’s instructions (see Note 21 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":195,"length":26}],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"9F2E7B18C7AF11EBBD120A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5326677/"}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9tsm0","text":"The following steps are for suspension cells, if working with adherent cells see Note 22 for steps on how to prepare the cells.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"23jo4","text":"Count out 1×107 cells as input for each fractionation, including a western blot control sample (see Note 23). If cell numbers are limited, fractionation can be performed on fewer cells (see Note 24).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4pd8","text":"Collect cells by centrifugation at 500g for 2 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"28mdk","text":"Wash with 10 ml of PBS (room temperature).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"523fi","text":"Collect cells by centrifugation at 500g for 2 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"69tpd","text":"Add spike-in cells (Drosophila S2, used for normalization) to the sample cells collected by centrifugation (the addition of a spike-in is optional, see Note 25).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"ch22c","text":"Repeat wash (step 3) and centrifugation (step 4).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5ch0u","text":"Remove supernatant by aspiration. It is important to remove the supernatant completely to avoid diluting the lysis buffer (see Note 26).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8iah3","text":"Using a cut P1000 pipette tip, add 200 µl of CLB to cells and mix by pipetting the sample up and down ten times. Transfer sample to an RNase-free 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube using a cut 1,000 µl pipette tip.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"1i4lc","text":"Incubate the cell lysate on ice for 5 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4gdjr","text":"During incubation period, pipette 500 µl of SB to an RNase-free 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ct8l8","text":"After incubation period, use a cut 1,000 µl pipette tip to layer the cell lysate sample onto the SB (see Note 27).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5ju2a","text":"Centrifuge layered lysate at 16,000g for 10 min at 4 °C to collect nuclei.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fgq9c","text":"Pipette off supernatant completely from the nuclei pellet (supernatant contains the cytoplasmic fraction, retain for western blot, described in Box 1)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e9lsd","text":"Wash nuclei pellet with 800 µl of NWB (either by inverting the tube or pipetting up and down).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"6apof","text":"Collect cell nuclei by centrifugation at 1,150g for 1 min at 4 °C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"94pum","text":"Pipette off supernatant from the nuclei pellet. It is important to remove the supernatant completely in order to remove cytoplasmic mature RNAs (see Note 26).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"15sl1","text":"Add 200 µl of GB to the nuclei. Use a cut 1,000 µl tip to resuspend the washed nuclei pellet by pipetting up and down.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bdglr","text":"Transfer the nuclei suspension to a new 1.5 ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4nrls","text":"Layer 200 µl of NLB onto nuclei suspension and mix by pulsed vortexing.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"1imh7","text":"Incubate the mixture on ice for 2 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3mopk","text":"Centrifuge at 18,500g for 2 min at 4 °C to collect the chromatin pellet.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4b8uj","text":"Pipette off supernatant from the chromatin pellet. It is important to completely remove the supernatant in order to remove nucleoplasmic RNAs (retain supernatant for the nucleoplasm fraction of western blot, described in Box 1).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9oks","text":"Add 50 µl CRS to the chromatin pellet, transfer pellet in CRS to a new 1.5 ml tube and then resuspend pellet in CRS (see Note 28). Perform this step on the experimental sample (for the preparation of nascent RNA, section 3.3.3) and the control sample (for the western blot analysis, as described in Box 1).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d824s","text":"Add 700 µl of QIAzol (lysis reagent in miRNeasy mini kit, Qiagen) to the resuspended chromatin (see Note 10 re QIAzol).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"37tvv","text":"Solubilize chromatin pellet by slowly pipetting up and down using a 1-ml syringe with a 22G needle (see Note 29). Mix very carefully (to avoid spilling the sample) until the solution is homogeneous.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"67qsr","text":"Prepare RNA using the miRNeasy mini kit (or miRNeasy micro kit for small cell numbers, see section 2.3.3 step 2) according to the manufacturer’s instructions, including optional DNase treatment.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bhjqr","text":"Measure the prepared RNA quantity and quality using a NanoDrop (see Note 30). The RNA yield is usually in the range of 20–30 µg (this can vary quite a lot depending on the type of cells used). If fractionation was performed on less than 1×107 cells (or RNA yield is less than 20 µg) see Note 24 re RNA amount needed to construct sequencing library. Store the isolated RNA at −80 °C (can be stored for months) until ready to construct sequencing library.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4 Constructing DNA sequencing library from isolated nascent RNA (Figure 1b)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"tmgl","text":"Spray down all work surfaces, pipettes, etc. with RNase away","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"76r6r","text":"Denature the RNA sample (from the cellular fractionation, section 3.3.3) and 5 µl of the oGAB11 control (10 µM; Table 1) for 2 min at 80 °C in a Thermomixer. Place on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d3d4d","text":"Prepare linker ligation mix for each RNA sample and for oGAB11 in 0.2-ml RNase-free PCR tubes. Mix until reaction is homogeneous, poor mixing will negatively affect the ligation efficiency.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9dgbh","text":"Add 1 µl Truncated T4 RNA ligase 2 (200U) to each RNA sample as well as the oGAB11 control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"63n56","text":"Incubate the ligation mixes for 10 - 16 hours at 16 °C in a thermal cycler (Note 31).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"38l","text":"Place on ice and add 0.7 µl of EDTA (0.5 M) to each ligation mix to stop the ligation reaction.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"7uqsr","text":"Perform fragmentation calibration test (see Box 2)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9viu7","text":"Add 20 µl of 2× alkaline fragmentation solution to each sample (from the ligation reaction) and mix. Do not perform fragmentation steps for the oGAB11 ligation control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4cfqo","text":"Incubate the sample at 95 °C in a thermal cycler for the calibrated time (see Box 2) to fragment RNA (see Note 32).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2sjrn","text":"To purify the fragmented RNA, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"e6kpj","text":"Prepare RNA ladder and un-ligated oGAB11 control by adding 1.0 µl of RNA control ladder or oGAB11 to 9 µl of RNase-free H2O. Add 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample to the RNA ladder and oGAB11 control, mix well (see Note 34).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"bok34","text":"Prepare all RNA samples (including the ligated oGAB11 control) by adding 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer to each sample, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"a64f8","text":"Denature the RNA sample, RNA control samples (ligated oGAB11 and un-ligated oGAB11 controls), and RNA ladder for 2 min at 80 °C. Place the samples on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cf33i","text":"Pre-run a 15% (wt/vol) polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel at 200 V for 15 min in 1× TBE. Thoroughly flush out gel wells prior to pre-running the gel (see Note 35).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"21pqa","text":"Load gel with the RNA ladder, RNA control samples (ligated oGAB11 and un-ligated oGAB11), and the fragmented RNA sample. Separate by PAGE at 200 V for 65 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"56m7m","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"52efh","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 3.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4nn79","text":"For the fragmented RNA sample, excise region between 40 and 110 nt. For the ligated oGAB11, excise a narrow band ~55 nt (see Note 36).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"83o30","text":"After rapid gel extraction is performed, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0) (at this point, RNA can be stored up to 3 months at -80 °C). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bh1hc","text":"The following steps are for suspension cells, if working with adherent cells see Note 22 in the Guidelines section for steps on how to prepare the cells.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ejioe","text":"Count out 1×107 cells as input for each fractionation, including a western blot control sample (see Note 23 in the Guidelines section). If cell numbers are limited, fractionation can be performed on fewer cells (see Note 24 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":14,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9g0au","text":"Collect cells by centrifugation at 500g for 2 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"3tnn","text":"Wash with 10 ml of PBS (room temperature).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"54j91","text":"Collect cells by centrifugation at 500g for 2 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7ab1s","text":"Add spike-in cells (Drosophila S2, used for normalization) to the sample cells collected by centrifugation (the addition of a spike-in is optional, see Note 25 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"fad2v","text":"Repeat wash (step 8) and centrifugation (step 9).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"crpfl","text":"Remove supernatant by aspiration. It is important to remove the supernatant completely to avoid diluting the lysis buffer (see Note 26 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"635n4","text":"Using a cut P1000 pipette tip, add 200 µl of CLB to cells and mix by pipetting the sample up and down ten times. Transfer sample to an RNase-free 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube using a cut 1,000 µl pipette tip.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"f4ga5","text":"Incubate the cell lysate on ice for 5 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2r4a9","text":"During incubation period, pipette 500 µl of SB to an RNase-free 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bcq4i","text":"After incubation period, use a cut 1,000 µl pipette tip to layer the cell lysate sample onto the SB (see Note 27 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d47fn","text":"Centrifuge layered lysate at 16,000g for 10 min at 4 °C to collect nuclei.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ajmt","text":"Pipette off supernatant completely from the nuclei pellet (supernatant contains the cytoplasmic fraction, retain for western blot, described in Box 1)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"flfnq","text":"Wash nuclei pellet with 800 µl of NWB (either by inverting the tube or pipetting up and down using a cut pipette tip).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"bdffr","text":"Collect cell nuclei by centrifugation at 1,150g for 1 min at 4 °C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c1g93","text":"Pipette off supernatant from the nuclei pellet. It is important to remove the supernatant completely in order to remove cytoplasmic mature RNAs (see Note 26 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2095m","text":"Add 200 µl of GB to the nuclei. Use a cut 1,000 µl tip to resuspend the washed nuclei pellet by pipetting up and down.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"80onc","text":"Transfer the nuclei suspension to a new 1.5 ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9dpv7","text":"Layer 200 µl of NLB onto nuclei suspension and briefly mix by pulsed vortexing.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"3km77","text":"Incubate the mixture on ice for 2 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1rlrl","text":"Centrifuge at 18,500g for 2 min at 4 °C to collect the chromatin pellet.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1uvdc","text":"Pipette off supernatant from the chromatin pellet. It is important to completely remove the supernatant in order to remove nucleoplasmic RNAs (retain supernatant for the nucleoplasm fraction of western blot, described in Box 1).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e55iv","text":"Add 50 µl CRS to the chromatin pellet, transfer pellet in CRS to a new 1.5 ml tube and then resuspend pellet in CRS (see Note 28 in the Guidelines section). Perform this step on the experimental sample (for the preparation of nascent RNA, section 1.3.3) and the control sample (for the western blot analysis, as described in Box 1).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d7dje","text":"Add 700 µl of QIAzol (lysis reagent in miRNeasy mini kit, Qiagen) to the resuspended chromatin (see Note 10 in the Guidelines section re QIAzol).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"428dq","text":"Solubilize chromatin pellet by slowly pipetting up and down using a 1-ml syringe with a 22G needle (see Note 29 in the Guidelines section). Mix very carefully (to avoid spilling the sample) until the solution is homogeneous (at this point the sample can be stored at −80 °C for months).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dngdg","text":"Prepare RNA using the miRNeasy mini kit (or miRNeasy micro kit for small cell numbers, see Materials section 1.3.3, Preparation of nascent RNA, step 2) according to the manufacturer’s instructions, including optional DNase treatment.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9ng3g","text":"Measure the prepared RNA quantity and quality using a NanoDrop (see Note 30 in the Guidelines section). The RNA yield is usually in the range of 20–30 µg (this can vary quite a lot depending on the type of cells used). If fractionation was performed on less than 1×107 cells (or RNA yield is less than 20 µg) see Note 24 in the Guidelines section re RNA amount needed to construct sequencing library. Store the isolated RNA at −80 °C (can be stored for months) until ready to construct sequencing library.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":267,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8lq7d","text":"Prepare linker ligation mix for each RNA sample and for oGAB11 in 0.2-ml RNase-free PCR tubes (see Materials section 1.4.1, Linker ligation, step 4). Mix until reaction is homogeneous, poor mixing will negatively affect the ligation efficiency.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":122,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"apt8i","text":"Add 1 µl Truncated T4 RNA ligase 2 (200U) to each RNA sample as well as the oGAB11 control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1k1om","text":"Incubate the ligation samples overnight for 10 - 16 hours at 16 °C in a thermal cycler (Note 31 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"a96rs","text":"Place on ice and add 0.7 µl of EDTA (0.5 M) to each ligation sample to stop the ligation reaction.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"ffuev","text":"Perform fragmentation calibration test (see Box 2)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c4g6k","text":"Add 20 µl of 2× alkaline fragmentation solution (see Materials section 1.4.2, RNA fragmentation, step 1) to each sample (from the ligation reaction) and mix. Do not perform fragmentation steps for the oGAB11 ligation control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":76,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"edt16","text":"Incubate the sample at 95 °C in a thermal cycler for the calibrated time (see Box 2) to fragment RNA (see Note 32 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1p6ps","text":"To purify the fragmented RNA, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"1tdq5","text":"Prepare RNA ladder and un-ligated oGAB11 control by adding 1.0 µl of RNA control ladder or oGAB11 to 9 µl of RNase-free H2O. Add 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample to the RNA ladder and oGAB11 control, mix well (see Note 34 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"5re9u","text":"Prepare all RNA samples (including the ligated oGAB11 control) by adding 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer to each sample, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"bea4m","text":"Denature the RNA sample, RNA control samples (ligated oGAB11 and un-ligated oGAB11 controls), and RNA ladder for 2 min at 80 °C. Place the samples on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4u6h1","text":"Pre-run a 15% (wt/vol) polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel at 200 V for 15 min in 1× TBE. Thoroughly flush out gel wells prior to pre-running the gel (see Note 35 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"c33rb","text":"Load gel with the RNA ladder, RNA control samples (ligated oGAB11 and un-ligated oGAB11), and the fragmented RNA sample. Separate by PAGE at 200 V for 65 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"503fr","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9cho","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"dbn0c","text":"For the fragmented RNA sample, excise region between 40 and 110 nt. For the ligated oGAB11, excise a narrow band ~55 nt (see Note 36 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"e1i4q","text":"Perform rapid gel extraction on the excised gel (see Box 3).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.3 Size select Fragmented RNA and perform gel extraction (Figure 2)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"a5vtv","text":"After rapid gel extraction is performed, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0) (at this point, RNA can be stored up to 3 months at -80 °C). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3hb7t","text":"Add 4.6 µl of RT reaction mix to 10 µl of the RNA sample and the oGAB11 control sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1890k","text":"Denature the sample mixtures (including the oGAB11 control) by incubating for 2 min at 80 °C in a thermal cycler. Place on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d7t6k","text":"Add 1.3 µl of SUPERase.In/DTT mix (see Materials section 1.4.4, Reverse Transcription, step 4) and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":62,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"bretm","text":"Add 0.8 µl of SuperScript III (200 U/µl) and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"66ndq","text":"Incubate for 30 min at 48 °C in a thermal cycler.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.5 Degradation of RNA after cDNA production (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"qp8b","text":"Add 1.8 µl of 1 N NaOH, mix well and incubate 20 min at 98 °C. This step degrades the RNA after cDNA was produced by RT.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.5 Degradation of RNA after cDNA production (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"61aek","text":"Neutralize the reaction by adding 1.8 µl of 1 N HCl; mix well and place on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7j2gt","text":"Prepare the DNA control ladder. Add 1.0 µl of DNA control ladder to 9 µl of RNase-free H2O. Add 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"54ead","text":"Add 20 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer to the cDNA sample and the oGAB11 cDNA control, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9mq2f","text":"Denature the cDNA sample, oGAB11 cDNA control and DNA control ladder for 3 min at 95 °C in a Thermomixer.  Place the samples on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)

Thoroughly flush out gel wells prior to pre-running the gel (see Note 35 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"do5j8","text":"Load gel (20 uL per lane, each sample will be split into two lanes) with the cDNA sample, the oGAB11 cDNA control and the DNA ladder. Separate by PAGE at 200 V for 65 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"1oq08","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"4p7t7","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"fjebt","text":"For the cDNA sample, excise region between ~85 and 160 nt (use oGAB11 as baseline and cut up ~70 nt). If no cDNA smear is observed see Note 37 in the Guidelines section.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6sur3","text":"Perform rapid gel extraction on the excised gel (see Box 3). steps.section: 1.4.6 Size select cDNA and gel extraction (Figure 3)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"3gaa2","text":"After rapid gel extraction is performed, use the Oligo kit (Zymo) and elute cDNA from column with 15 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 8.0) (at this point, the cDNA can be stored indefinitely at −20 °C). Alternatively, cDNA can be prepared by precipitation (see Note 33 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"963k2","text":"In a 0.2-ml RNase-free PCR tube, add 4 µl of circularization mix to 15 µl of the cDNA sample and the oGAB11 cDNA control sample, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"dchkp","text":"Add 1 µl of CircLigase (100 U/µl) and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6i0vl","text":"Incubate the CircLigase reaction for 60 min at 60 °C and then 10 min at 80 °C in a thermal cycler. Circularized cDNA can be stored indefinitely at −20 °C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7oq28","text":"Optional: at this point a specific depletion of highly abundant mature RNAs can be performed (see Note 38 in the Guidelines section)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

Mix well and store on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":141,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"st41","text":"After centrifugation, add 670 µl of DNA soaking buffer and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"alvmk","text":"Incubate the samples overnight at room temperature in a Thermomixer (set at 1,500 r.p.m.).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d4et7","text":"Use a cut 1,000 µl pipette tip to transfer the gel slurry into a microcentrifuge tube filter.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dir3v","text":"Centrifuge at 20,000g for 3 min at room temperature. Transfer the eluate to a new 1.5 ml microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8797t","text":"Precipitate the NET-seq library by adding 2 µl of 15 mg/ml GlycoBlue and 680 µl of isopropanol. Mix well then incubate the precipitations at −20 °C for ≥1 h (the DNA precipitations can be stored at −20 °C overnight).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"djuev","text":"Centrifuge at 20,000g for 30 min at 4 °C to pellet the RNA.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1iq2h","text":"Remove the supernatant and wash the pellet with 750 µl of 80% (vol/vol) ice-cold ethanol.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"69vti","text":"Spin the sample at 20,000g for 2 min at 4 °C, and then remove the supernatant. Air-dry the RNA pellet for 10 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7ov2e","text":"Resuspend the NET-seq library in 7 - 10 µl of Tris-HCl (10 mM, pH 8.0). The DNA sequencing library can be stored indefinitely at −20 °C.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.11 Quantification and characterization of NET-seq library (Figure 4)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9tpr3","text":"Prepare a 1:5 dilution of the NET-seq library by adding 1 µl of the NET-seq library to 4 µl of Tris-HCl (10 mM, pH 8.0); mix well (see Note 40 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.11 Quantification and characterization of NET-seq library (Figure 4)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6vp5f","text":"Use 1 µl of the diluted NET-seq library for quantification with the Qubit fluorometer using the Qubit dsDNA HS assay kit. Prepare the sample and perform the measurement according to the manufacturer’s protocol (see Note 41 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.11 Quantification and characterization of NET-seq library (Figure 4)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cec4u","text":"Use 1 µl of the diluted NET-seq library for characterization on the Agilent Bioanalyzer; use the high-sensitivity DNA analysis kit according to the manufacturer’s instructions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.4.11 Quantification and characterization of NET-seq library (Figure 4)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"2q4f3","text":"Sequence using oLSC006. Sequence the human NET-seq library from the 3′ end (75 bp single-end sequencing) on the Illumina platform using oLSC006 (Table 1 in the Materials section) as a custom sequencing primer. Perform sequencing according to the manufacturer’s instructions. NET-seq libraries are typically sequenced on MiSeq, HiSeq or NextSeq next-generation sequencing platforms. A reasonable coverage is obtained with 100–200 million reads.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"25kdp","text":"Assess read quality control with FastQC.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dt255","text":"Displace 5’ end random barcode sequence from sequence to read identifier line and save as a separate fastq file. This barcode serves as a unique molecular identifier (UMI) and originates from the linker (see Table 1 in the Materials section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"chtfb","text":"Align fastq files with and without UMI sequences separately to a human reference genome using STAR (See Note 43 in the Guidelines section). In case a Drosophila spike-in was used, concatenate the human and Drosophila fasta files to generate a combined reference genome.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.5.2 Filter out read alignments that do not reflect RNA polymerase position.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6mr9a","text":"Remove alignments resulting from RT mispriming events, i.e. cases where RT priming did not occur at the complementary sequence site on the ligated linker but instead at a position within the RNA fragment. The resulting reads can be identified as they lack the random UMI sequence encoded on the linker and therefore align well to the reference genome both with and without UMI displacement: when the STAR alignment score of a read with the UMI sequence equals the UMI length (10nt) plus the alignment score from that read without UMI.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.5.2 Filter out read alignments that do not reflect RNA polymerase position.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"5sain","text":"Remove alignments that map to multiple genomic locations by filtering for their MAPQ value (\u003c 50) using samtools.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.5.2 Filter out read alignments that do not reflect RNA polymerase position.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cn7k1","text":"Remove alignments resulting from PCR duplication events, i.e. cases of multiple amplicons that originate from the same RNA fragment. The resulting multiple reads are bioinformatically indistinguishable as their alignments share the same position, strand, chromosome, UMI sequence and CIGAR score. To filter out these PCR duplicates, we maintain only one of the alignments.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.5.2 Filter out read alignments that do not reflect RNA polymerase position.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"1t4ah","text":"Remove alignments that could arise from splicing intermediates, i.e. 3’ ends of annotated exons and introns.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: 1.5.3 Determine RNA polymerase coverage genome-wide from read alignments.
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"5fcfm","text":"Use HTseq to generate a coverage (bedgraph) file containing the read counts at a base-pair resolution over the reference genome as determined from the 5’ end of the read alignments (without UMI) on the opposite strand. The resulting positions correspond to the 3’ ends of nascent RNA and thereby map RNA polymerase positions. The coverage files will be used for a variety of downstream bioinformatics analyses such as visual inspection (e.g. using IGV), metagene profiling (e.g. Bedtools), differential expression (e.g. DEseq2).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"2tlk9","text":"The western blot control is used to determine whether or not the cellular fractionation protocol has been executed successfully. The efficiency of the fractionation can be quantified by measuring the amount of elongating Pol II captured in the chromatin fraction (ideally  ≥95%). When the fractionation protocol is being performed for the first time or being tested on a new cell type, the cytoplasm, nucleoplasm, and chromatin fractions should be checked for subcellular marker proteins (see Note 5 in the Guidelines section) to confirm the fractionation is working (see Note 20 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"eimtn","text":"Adjust the nucleoplasmic (from steps 1.3.2) and chromatin fraction (from steps 1.3.2) volumes to the cytoplasmic fraction (from steps 1.3.1) volume by adding 1× PBS. Mix each fraction well and ensure the chromatin pellet is completely resuspended (see Note 7 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9np9m","text":"Add 50 µl of 2× SDS buffer (see Materials section 1.3.2, Isolation of chromatin fraction, step 7) to 50 µl of each subcellular fraction and boil the samples at 95 °C for 5 min (at this point, samples can be stored for months at −20 °C).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"2lb42","text":"Separate samples by standard SDS-PAGE (loading 10 µl of each boiled sample per lane is usually sufficient).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Box 1 | Western blot control: checking cell fractionation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6fhnr","text":"Probe the membrane overnight at 4 °C with Pol II CTD Ser2-P antibody (3E10, 1:1,000 dilution) and Pol II CTD Ser5-P antibody (3E8, 1:1,000 dilution). These antibodies target transcribing RNA Pol II (see Note 6 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"38ll5","text":"Take 9 samples of RNA (~1ug each) from a total RNA sample (or any other easily obtained RNA sample). Re-suspend each RNA sample in 8uL of RNase-free water and add 12uL of the linker ligation mix, excluding the linker and ligase (see Materials section 1.4.1, Linker ligation, step 4). Add 20 µl of 2× alkaline fragmentation solution (see Materials section 1.4.2, RNA fragmentation, step 1) to each sample and mix well (see Note 32 in the Guidelines section); fragmentation is not performed for the oGAB11 control.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":251,"length":6},{"style":"bold","offset":360,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3md9c","text":"Fragment each RNA sample at 95 °C in a thermal cycler for the following times: 0, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, and 50 minutes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1he61","text":"To purify the fragmented RNA, use the RNA Clean \u0026 Concentrator-5 kit (Zymo) and elute RNA from column with 10 uL of 10 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0). Alternatively, RNA can be prepared by RNA precipitation (see Note 33 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8foqd","text":"Prepare RNA ladder (denoted as L in figure) by adding 1.0 µl of RNA control ladder to 9 µl of RNase-free H2O. Add 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample to the RNA ladder and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"72ofp","text":"Prepare all RNA samples by adding 10 µl of 2× TBU denaturing sample buffer to each sample, mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"682td","text":"Denature the RNA sample and RNA ladder for 2 min at 80 °C. Place the samples on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"adqd8","text":"Pre-run a 15% (wt/vol) polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel at 200 V for 15 min in 1× TBE. Thoroughly flush out gel wells prior to pre-running the gel (see Note 35 in the Guidelines section).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1devf","text":"Load gel with the RNA ladder and the fragmented RNA sample. Separate by PAGE at 200 V for 65 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bkhrg","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cdifr","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light. The optimal fragmentation time is when most RNA molecules are in the required size range, between 40 and 110 nt (the optimal fragmentation time in the figure below is between 25 and 30 minutes).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e65jh","text":"Use a 21G needle to pierce the bottom of a 0.5-ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6caq4","text":"Place the pierced 0.5-ml tube into a 1.5-ml RNase-free microcentrifuge tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d5eiv","text":"Put the gel slice (from fragmentation, RT, or PCR) into the pierced 0.5-ml tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"54m88","text":"Centrifuge the nestled tubes, containing the gel slice, at 20,000g for 4 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"1frir","text":"Add 200 µl of RNase-free H2O to the chopped-up gel and mix.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"7595h","text":"Incubate the sample mixture for 10 min at 70 °C in a Thermomixer.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"7tbva","text":"Vortex the mixture for 30 s at medium intensity.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"di537","text":"Cut the tip off of a 1,000-µl pipette tip and transfer the gel mixture into a microcentrifuge tube filter.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"ena7d","text":"Centrifuge the mixture at 20,000g for 3 min at room temperature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dh3n4","text":"Prepare the PCR master mix (see Materials section 1.4.8, PCR amplification, step 4) for four pilot PCR amplifications for each cDNA sample and the oGAB11 cDNA control sample (denoted as O in figure). Mix well and store it on ice.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8rjvk","text":"For each PCR sample, put 19 µl of PCR master mix in a 0.2-ml RNase-free PCR tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"crhh7","text":"Add 1 µl of circularized cDNA and mix it well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9j37b","text":"Perform PCR pilot amplifications (described in Table 2). Remove one PCR tube for each sample at the end of the extension step after 6, 8, 10 and 12 amplification cycles.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"cmfol","text":"Add 3.4 µl of 6× DNA loading dye to each tube and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c11a3","text":"Prepare DNA control ladder (denoted as L in figure) by adding 1.0 µl of ladder to 9 µl of DNase-free H2O. Then add 2 µl of 6× DNA loading dye and mix well.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"321m4","text":"Separate the PCR products and the DNA control ladder by TBE gel electrophoresis on an 8% (wt/vol) TBE gel at 180 V for 55 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3flse","text":"Stain the gel in 50 ml of gel staining solution (see Materials section 1.4.8, PCR amplification) for 5 min at room temperature on a shaker (use a black gel box to protect gel from light while staining).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"bc6q3","text":"Visualize the gel under blue/UV light and identify the optimal PCR amplification cycles for each cDNA sequencing library. The optimal PCR amplification cycles for the NET-seq library, which runs at ~150 nt, is determined by the presence of a clear band at ~150 nt and no higher-molecular-weight PCR products (the optimal number of cycles in the figure above is between 6 and 8).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3ifj6","text":"Performing RNA fragmentation results in a homogeneous RNA pool which helps to avoid length biases in any downstream enzymatic reactions. {"blocks":[{"key":"6hej1","text":"This protocol for rapidly extracting RNA or cDNA from a polyacrylamide TBE-urea gel is similar to the gel extraction protocol described by the Weissman laboratory (Ingolia et al. 2012; Churchman and Weissman 2012).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"drnp6","text":"The NET-seq library is PCR amplified using an Illumina index forward primer (Barcode primer, see Table 1 in the Materials section) and a reverse primer (oNTI231; Table 1 in the Materials section) specific to NET-seq (Figure 4). For each NET-seq library preparation, the minimum number of PCR cycles needed to obtain a sequencing library must to be determined. The NET-seq library is then amplified with the determined minimal amount of PCR cycles; this avoids overamplification which can result in unwanted products such as PCR duplicates.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
